WIZEN is most commonly used as the past participle, as in a wrinkled, WIZENed old man.

BRAVA is simply the feminine of BRAVo, the proper way to applaud a female performer who has done a bang-up job.

@Wolf
"Wizen" means "to dry up, shrivel, as with age." Unsually used with plants or fruit (think those old granny smiths in the back of your fridge), but also used by extension for people. The verb for "to become wise" is, well, "wise," but it's usually used in a slightly derogatory way, like "to wise up." The two words have different etymologies, BTW.

"Brava" is the feminine form of the Italian adjective "bravo," used when the person being applauded is a woman. Opera Queens (of which I am one) love to scream "Brava!", hypercorrectly, after a  favorite diva has finished her aria.

